==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|þunor}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*þunraz}}, from *þen, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*(s)tenh₂-||to thunder}}. Germanic cognates include West Frisian {{m|fy|tonger}}, Dutch {{m|nl|donder}}, German {{m|de|Donner}}. Other cognates include [[w:Persian language|Persian]] {{m|fa|تندر|tr=tondar}}, Latin {{m|la|tonō}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈθʌn.də/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|thŭn'dər}}, {{IPA|/ˈθʌn.dɚ/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-thunder.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ʌndə(ɹ)|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun|~}}

# The [[sound]] caused by the discharge of atmospheric electrical charge.
#: '''''Thunder''' ''is preceded by [[lightning]].''
# A sound resembling thunder; especially, one produced by a [[jet]] [[airplane]] in flight.
# A deep, [[rumble|rumbling]] noise.
#: ''Off in the distance, he heard the '''thunder''' of hoofbeats, signalling a stampede.''
# An alarming or startling [[threat]] or [[denunciation]].
#* Prescott
#*: The '''thunders''' of the Vatican could no longer strike into the heart of princes.
# {{label|en|obsolete}} The [[discharge]] of [[electricity]]; a [[thunderbolt]].
#* Shakespeare
#*: The revenging gods / 'Gainst parricides did all their '''thunders''' bend.
# {{label|en|figuratively}} The [[spotlight]].

